The governing equilibrium equation of the traditional dynamic model can be given by two coupled differential equations
(5){mav··a+Ca(v·a-v·b)+Ka(va-vb)=p(t)mbv··b-Ca(v·a-v·b)-Ka(va-vb)+Cbv·b+Kbvb=0
and in matrix form
(6)[m]{V··}+[C]{V·}+[K]{V}={P(t)}
where
[m]=[ma00mb],[C]=[Ca-Ca-CaCa+Cb],[K]=[Ka-Ka-KaKa+Kb],{V}={vavb}and{P(t)}={p(t)0}

The angular velocity ω of main and auxiliary crankshaft is a constant. Taking B0 and F0 as the starting point of displacement for slider s3 and displacement for additional weight s6, as shown in Figure 4. As λ1 and λ2 are much less than 0.3, the acceleration of main slider and auxiliary weight can be expressed as
(15)a3=ω2R1(cosα+λ1cos2α)a6=ω2R2(cosα+λ2cos2α)}
where λ1=R1/L1, λ2=R2/L2.

The acceleration of mass center C has three components a3, a2n, a2τ and the acceleration of mass center G also has three components a6, a5n, a5τ. The normal and tangential acceleration can be given
(16)a2n=λ12ω2LCcosαa2τ=-λ1ω2LCsinα}
(17)a5n=λ22ω2LFcosαa5τ=-λ2ω2LFsinα}
